    description: "California's AB5 codified the ABC test from the Dynamex decision, creating the strictest worker classification standard in the country. Under the ABC test, a worker is presumed to be an employee unless the hiring entity proves ALL THREE prongs: (A) the worker is free from the control and direction of the hiring entity, (B) the worker performs work outside the usual course of the hiring entity's business, and (C) the worker is customarily engaged in an independently established trade, occupation, or business. Prong B is devastating for gyms: personal training IS the usual course of a gym's business. This means most gym trainers in California are employees by default unless they qualify for a specific AB5 exemption (e.g., the business-to-business exemption). The consequences of misclassification in California include back taxes, wages, penalties, and potential criminal prosecution.",
